8</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Sophie</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Maria</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>von Stumm</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FI010173%2F1"><gtr:id>E9187853-2BB1-453A-90D4-FFF4F8DA4336</gtr:id><gtr:title>Postdoctoral Fellowship: The relationship of intelligence and personality, and its effect on adult intellect.</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I010173/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Sophie von Stumm?s doctoral research explored associations of intelligence and personality, the core pillars of the psychology of Individual Differences. Personality traits were hypothesised to affect &lt;em>when, where and how&lt;/em> people apply and invest their intelligence, thereby shaping knowledge and skills attainment across the life-span. The work focused in particular on the effects of &lt;em>intellectual investment traits&lt;/em> - that is, individual differences in the need and pleasure of thinking and information seeking - on adult intellect.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>In a series of meta-analytic studies, a multitude of intellectual investment constructs to develop a unifying framework where reviewed. Furthermore, investment traits were found to enhance adult intellect, and this association remained significant after controlling for other well-established predictors of intellect.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>Subsequently, Sophie proposed to conceptualise &lt;em>intellectual investment&lt;/em> as multi-faceted trait dimension of &lt;em>curiosity&lt;/em>. Testing large samples of students and military officers using novel psychometric tests, curiosity was related to increased knowledge beyond effects of intelligence, supporting a developmental perspective on intelligence-personality associations. Overall, a hungry mind was shown to be a crucial factor in intellectual growth.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>Sophie will fully disseminate and expand this doctoral research during this ESRC fellowship, hosted at the University of Edinburgh under the mentorship of Professor Ian Deary.&lt;/p>

