-2056165795.82557632b134fc8</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:year>2012</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>During this post-doctoral fellowship, investment personality traits, which refer to the tendency to continuously seek out and engage in effortful cognitive activity, were found to positively affect intelligence in adulthood. Specifically, investment traits were associated with several indicators of adult intellect; thus, they related to better academic performance, higher crystallized intelligence, and greater knowledge.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Knowing that investments in one's intellect pay off, as they result in higher intelligence and better cognitive functioning, is useful to the general public as well as settings that concentrate specifically on knowledge transfer, such as schools. This research is relevant for (1) educational settings that aim to inspire and encourage students' learning; (2) understanding adult intellectual functioning and development; and (3) managing age-related effects on intelligence. It also highlights that intelligence and personality are intertwined rather than separate entities and thus, progresses future research in both areas.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>2EC837B0-9765-4A10-91BF-BFE8FF231885</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>r-3974169915.5179505b2f2fadc</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Creative Economy,Education,Leisure Activities, including Sports, Recreation and Tourism,Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>http://www.hungrymindlab.com</gtr:url></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutpu